body:
@bep mate he's the project maintainer, the second he merges in "your code", it becomes his responsibility to maintain it. When it breaks, he has to fix it. During refactoring, he has to include that code. Really, the second it merges into his repo, it's not "your code" anymore. It's completely normal to ask for tests, documentation, refactoring, or to even simply reject a patch if it doesn't meet the maintainer's (subjective) standards. That's the point of being a maintainer.

I can't tell from a glance whose patch makes "more sense" or "is cleaner", so you may very well be objectively right, here. Nonetheless; your comment is uncalled for. Submit a PR, or don't, and move on. Don't make it personal.

Maintaining an open source project is more than just green lighting patches from strangers. It's unrewarding, ungrateful work, and comments like this can be demoralising.
